Replying to @Sam Bivans   Can you tell the difference? The Philodendron White Knight, Wizard, and Princess are so similar, this has been the easiest way for me to identify them! #plantsoftiktok #plantparent #plantsmakemehappy #houseplants #philodendron #philodendronwhiteknight #philodendronwhiteprincess #philodendronwhitewizard #planthelp
voice_to_text: So I've gotten this question a lot of what's the difference between a philodendron white knight, white wizard, and white princess? And I have all 3 of my collection now so I can show you. In terms of care and growth, habit would say that all 3 of these are incredibly similar. And as you can tell by the foliage, they look a lot alike. So if you're trying to go just based off of the leaves, you're probably gonna have a hard time. The secret and telling the difference with these babies is going to be looking at the stems. A philodendron White Princess is going to have green stems with pink variegation along the margin. It is rare, but it can happen that a white Princess pushes out pink variegation instead of white, but it usually is going to fade to white eventually. The White Wizard looks really similar, but the stem is going to be completely green, no signs of pink. And lastly, the philodendron White Knight is going to have a darker red kind of burgundy stem, and that's going to be really apparent, especially on that new growth. Let me know what's your favorite!

Perfect companion for basil, cucumbers and brassicas such as kale, cabbage, broccoli, cauliflower, kale, Brussels sprouts, kohlrabi, turnips, radishes. Their aroma deters cabbage pests. That’s what I had growing in these beds last year. This year, I will need to clear the space to make room for gourds (squashes and melons). She attracts a lot of pollinators. I’ve seen lady bugs and bees visit her a lot. The one bunch of seedling actually multiplied to 2 bundles as seen here. I spread her a little so it doesn’t suffocate the Thyme near her. I am calling her Camilla as she is becoming a force in my garden. Looks like she’s is a German Chamomile as supposed to a Roman Chamomile. The German chamomile is about 24”, prolific bloomer, an annual, dies after flowering but set seeds that comes back the following year while a Roman Chamomile is a perennial and shorter in size. I actually saved some seeds last year but learning now that I may not need them. Will save for the flowers for loose tea instead. Chamomile is known as a good herbal tea for calming the stomach and anxiety and promoting sleep. However it may not be good for people with asthma especially with allergies to ragweed or the asteraceae family (ie. aster, daisies, chrysanthemums, etc.) 🤔🤚🏼😳  I’m afraid if I don’t relocate or cut her back soon she will sow her seeds everywhere and will grow all over my beautiful rock bed. I will keep you posted but in the meantime, join me in enjoying her beauty. #garden #chamomile #chamomiletea #germanchamomile #herbal #herb #plants #companionplanting #zone6b
